$\dfrac{dx}{dt}=-\dfrac{3x}{y}$ [[☃ explanation 1]]

### Finding $\dfrac{dx}{dt}$ at $(2,5)$

The expression for $\dfrac{dx}{dt}$ depends on both the particle's $x$-coordinate $\blueD{2}$ and its $y$-coordinate $\maroonD{5}$:

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{dx}{dt}&=-\dfrac{3(\blueD{2})}{(\maroonD{5})}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{6}{5}
\end{align}$

### Finding $\dfrac{dx}{dt}$

